	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">My Politics</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sparrow">Sparrow</a></li><li><a href="/issues/309">September 2001</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p>My personal life is particularly political. In fact, now that I ponder the subject, I see that I was one of the first personal-as-political activists. Here is a list of my achievements:</p>

<ol>
    <li>I have not watched television for twenty-eight years.</li>
    <li>I have not eaten meat for twenty-nine years.</li>
    <li>I have meditated every day for twenty-six years.</li>
    <li>I have worked full time for a total of nine and a half months. (The rest of my working life &mdash; twenty-seven years &mdash; I have worked part time.)</li>
    <li>The most money I have made in a year is $11,806.</li>
</ol>

<p>But these are just my most visible accomplishments. Please accompany me through an account of my personal political life:</p>

<p><strong>June 4</strong><br />
I speak to Julie on the phone. The conversation turns to fleas. (Julie has two cats.) &ldquo;We&rsquo;ve had severe infestations,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;I go through their fur two or three times a day, looking very carefully for fleas.&rdquo;</p>

<p>This piques my sadistic curiosity. &ldquo;How do you kill the fleas?&rdquo; I ask. &ldquo;Do you drown them in kerosene?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I just put them in water. Soapy water or plain water.&rdquo;</p>

<p>There is a thoughtful pause in the conversation.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Actually, I like fleas,&rdquo; Julie reflects. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry I have to kill them. I admire their tenacity, their talent for survival. And they can leap really far!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Good,&rdquo; I reply. &ldquo;I am happy to hear of your love for fleas.&rdquo;</p>

<p>To express love for the despised and the forgotten &mdash; particularly fleas, who have no voice in the human world &mdash; that is real politics.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 6</strong><br />
My mother-in-law gave us curtains of a heavy olive-colored fabric decorated with flowers &mdash; almost a camouflage pattern. These curtains shut out the light so well that, even on a bright morning, the room is dim, and you cannot distinguish the pants hanging in the closet.</p>

<p>Nevertheless, at these moments, I never turn on the light; rather, I go to the window and pull open the curtain. Why waste the earth&rsquo;s riches, in the form of electricity, when the purest sunlight is available for scant exertion?</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 10</strong><br />
When I&rsquo;m walking down a street and need to spit (I have become quite a spitter in the last six years), I pause to consider: Where can I best bestow my spit? What flower or tree is most desperate for whatever nourishment my spit can provide?</p>

<p>Suppose I see a yellowing, four-inch-high plant with spoon-shaped double leaves and a thick brownish stem. Before spitting, I attempt to guess whether this creature is thirsting. If I suppose that she is, I give her my small feast of saliva. These are my politics.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 12</strong><br />
On the stone wall of a toilet stall at the college in New Paltz, a man has scratched, <span class="smallcaps">DEATH TO</span> &mdash; followed by the ugliest word in the American language, a word used to justify slavery and vigilante murder.</p>

<p>Luckily, I always carry a felt-tip pen, so I quickly cross out this last word and then deliberate over what to put in its place. Should I write, <span class="smallcaps">DEATH TO WHITES</span>? Or, <span class="smallcaps">DEATH TO IDIOTS</span>? Or, <span class="smallcaps">DEATH TO RACISTS</span>?</p>

<p>Finally, I settle on <span class="smallcaps">DEATH TO BIGOTRY</span>, proud that I have chosen to kill an abstract wrong rather than a group of humans.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 17</strong><br />
When we moved into a new apartment, a relative gave us plastic plates. They are off-white and flat, with a little rim. In the manner of plastic plates, they have no ornamentation. They are so simple that there&rsquo;s even something aesthetically clever about them. Yet I do not use them.</p>

<p>I make it a point to use the china plate left to us by my wife&rsquo;s grandmother, which has roses and sprigs of ferns pictured on it. There is a tradition of china plates that goes back centuries, and plastic breaks that tradition. Touching plastic to your sandwich is like gargling with contact-lens fluid. It introduces that alien technological presence, that sense of self-disrespect that is so modern.</p>

<p>Why don&rsquo;t I discard the plastic plates? I can answer that with a joke: A Jew is stranded on a desert island and builds two synagogues. When he&rsquo;s rescued by a passing ship, the captain asks him: &ldquo;Why did you build two synagogues?&rdquo;</p>

<p>He points to the first one. &ldquo;This one I go to every week,&rdquo; he says. Then he points to the second: &ldquo;And this one I wouldn&rsquo;t set foot in!&rdquo;</p>

<p>For me, the plastic plates serve this purpose. They are a spiritual temptation to resist. (And they might be useful someday, if we have a lot of guests.)</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 19</strong><br />
An overweight man boards the bus in Rosendale, carrying many bags. He stops opposite me and opens the luggage compartment above the seat. <em>Whamp!</em> An enormous knock on my head. I look up and see that he has slammed me with his shoulder bag. He hasn&rsquo;t even noticed that he hit me.</p>

<p>I am angry and wish to shout: &ldquo;Watch where you swing that deadly shoulder bag, you fat egomaniac!&rdquo;</p>

<p>But I realize he did not mean to harm me, and he would learn nothing from my angry outburst. Instead, I will remain silent and consider the possibility that this pain is karma for some previous thoughtless deed of my own.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>June 27</strong><br />
A grave problem facing this nation is its name &mdash; or rather its lack of one. &ldquo;The United States&rdquo; is more of a description. Most nations are groups of united states. What else would they be? &ldquo;The United States of America&rdquo; is misleading, since America is a huge area comprising two whole continents, and this nation does not unite all its states. A more precise name would be &ldquo;Some United States of North America, Plus Hawaii,&rdquo; or <span class="smallcaps">susoNAPH</span>, for short. And of course, &ldquo;America&rdquo; is so hubristic as to be almost funny. Why not call ourselves &ldquo;Earth&rdquo;?</p>

<p>Isn&rsquo;t there a name that describes what&rsquo;s distinct about our nation, the way &ldquo;France&rdquo; seems to capture something quintessentially French?</p>

<p>Hope arrives today in the form of a <em>New York Times</em> article titled &ldquo;Ancient Site Offers Clues to Vikings in America: Ruins Tell of a Norse Settlement&rdquo;:</p>

<blockquote>
<p>Sometime at the end of the tenth century .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. [Leif] Ericson set out from the Greenland colony in his sturdy longboat with a soaring prow and a large square sail. Another seafarer, drifting off course, had sighted land to the west, and Ericson went to see for himself.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Here, at L&rsquo;Anse aux Meadows [Newfoundland], they established the base camp, their beachhead in Vinland.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Of Vinland, Adam of Bremen wrote in 1070, &ldquo;There grow wild grapes.&rdquo;</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Vinland! How succulent and true this name rings! We are a land of grapes and berries. Why, just this morning, I stopped on my way across New Paltz to sample some ripe mulberries &mdash; dangling black amid a tree&rsquo;s profuse leafage. Sweet Vinland! This is the name I will use forever.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>July 2</strong><br />
In Gainesville, Florida, the public library has paintings. For three weeks, you can borrow a little Juan Gris still life and mount it on your wall. You live with this painting &mdash; of a fish on a plate and two pears &mdash; for most of a month, and then it moves on, to a new apartment or house. A short woman named Allison, perhaps, will have it next.</p>

<p>I believe in the expansion of libraries to embrace all things: place mats, wrenches, chess sets &mdash; even food. Suppose a woman (let&rsquo;s call her Mrs. Culver) buys a box of oatmeal at the Boiceville Market. At home, Mrs. Culver opens the box and discovers it&rsquo;s cinnamon-flavored. She despises cinnamon oatmeal. So she brings the box to the Pine Hill Library, and an elderly man &mdash; a Mr. Gormar &mdash; checks out the oatmeal. For twenty-one years, he has wondered whether he would enjoy cinnamon-flavored oatmeal. (He is too parsimonious to buy an extra box of oatmeal.) Now, due to Mrs. Culver&rsquo;s error, he discovers that he does enjoy cinnamon oatmeal!</p>

<p>This is the library I envision.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>July 10</strong><br />
In the morning, as I await my bus to New Paltz, the cold sometimes forces me into the <span class="smallcaps">ATM</span> shelter at the Key Bank. Today three insects were crawling on the inside of the glass door. They were thin green beings, winged, considerably smaller than flies. I watched their progress for a time and gradually deduced that they were trapped in the <span class="smallcaps">ATM</span> room. I opened the door to set them free, but they did not escape. So I blew on one. She faltered for a moment, then fled by air.</p>

<p>I blew on the next. She, too, drifted off.</p>

<p>I blew on the third. He was freed.</p>

<p>Then I continued to wait for the bus.</p>

<hr />
<p><em>A different version of this essay originally appeared in </em>Ulster<em> magazine.</em></p>
														</div>


				
